Hi Mark,

Can you provide some of the actual errors that you see/code examples with these questions please, it would really make looking at them a lot easier.

When you call `pybindJSON.load` or `pybindJSON.loads` then yes, they expect that they need to go and create an instance of a class that you give it (hence the `python_module` and `yang_module` arguments. However, if you look at this code, these are just wrappers around the actual work - which is done by `serialise.pybindJSONDecoder.load_json`. This code can handle the case where it is supplied an existing object (since it actually calls itself recursively to load). This means that you can use `load_json` with a specified pre-existing object.

For example, if one has the following YANG:

```yang
module "test" {
    prefix "t";
    namespace "http://rob.sh/yang/t";
    
    container load-one {
        leaf item {
            type int8;
        }
    }

    container load-two {
        leaf item {
            type int8;
        }
    }
}
```

Then the following code allows loading the entire object vs. individual containers.

```
#!/usr/bin/env python

import tmp
import json
from pyangbind.lib.xpathhelper import YANGPathHelper
from pyangbind.lib.pybindJSON import dumps,loads
from pyangbind.lib.serialise import pybindJSONDecoder

yh = YANGPathHelper()

c1 = """
{
    "item": 101
}
"""

c2 = """
{
    "item": 102
}
"""

oall = """
{
    "load-one": {
        "item": 1
    },
    "load-two": {
        "item": 2
    }
}"""


print "Full:"
# There is a silly bug here, whereby if you actually give loads a string, then it balks
# because it expects something to have parsed the JSON already. This is counter
# intuitive and hence has been fixed, but in a backwards compatible way
nh = loads(json.loads(oall), tmp, "test", path_helper=yh)
print dumps(nh)

print "Partial:"
pybindJSONDecoder().load_json(json.loads(c1), False, False, obj=nh.load_one, path_helper=yh, overwrite=True)
print dumps(nh)
```

I'm not clear what you mean by `PybindBase` class - there isn't ever such a thing - `PybindBase` is just used by all classes that are generated by pyangbind for method inheritance, no such class is ever instantiated. The JSON decoder is specifically looking for a class called `safe_name(yang_module)` inside the `python_module` module that you supply to it (this is because it calls `load_json` with no obj= argument, so `load_json` tries to find the module that is being referred to).

It would, of course, be possible to add a pair of helper methods in pybindJSON called something like `loads_partial` and `load_partial` that would wrap the above - it's quite trivial. I'm happy to look at a pull-req for that.

