I'm using it to produce JavaScript code that its used to interface with other JS libraries and it avoids most of the mind context-switching burden while coding both Python and JS code. As I said, while Transcrypt saves you from the knowledge of some JavaScript initially, as soon as you interface your code with other JS library code you will have to take both JavaScript AND Transcrypt into account.

Let's say, for example, that your Python loop is in a function "do_something(options)" which is called by external JS code (where "options" is the "dict" you loop on).  The function is like:

```python

def do_something(options):
    for k, v in options.items():
        print(k, v) # do something better here
```

Transcrypt converts it to something like:
```javascript
var do_something = function (options) {
    var __iterable0__ = options.py_items ();
    for (var __index0__ = 0; __index0__ < __iterable0__.length; __index0__++) {
        var __left0__ = __iterable0__ [__index0__];
        var k = __left0__ [0];
        var v = __left0__ [1];
        print (k, v);
    }
};
```
Assuming that the external JS code is creating such "options" dict,  to ensure that your loop will not blow in your face using Transcrypt, you are forced to convert your "best practice" Python code to something like:

```python

def do_something(options):
    options = dict(options)
    for k, v in options.items():
        print(k, v) # do something better here
```

This to ensure that the "options" value will have that "py_items()" method defined no matter who calls it. (See https://github.com/QQuick/Transcrypt/blob/4d3cf1fa77aa87a65cd9afb3fff1b38079721cee/transcrypt/modules/org/transcrypt/__javascript__/__builtin__.mod.js#L1294 ) 

So Transcrypt maybe does a better job if  you know nothing about JavaScript and your code does not interface with external JS libraries. Because if it does, you will end up doing "not so pythonic code" anyway. With the notable inconvenience that maybe you have written your code and tests in Python translated to JS and all is doing well, but as soon as you "plug it in" to work with your JS library of preference it will start having issues and you will have an hard day of finding bugs and fixing them, or you will end up rewriting you external JS library in Transcrypt and you will almost die of boredom.

I don't want to do that and i don't want to reinvent the wheel transforming an existent JS library in simil-Python code. I do prefer a more "straight" approach, where the developer is more conscious of the final JS environment where his code will run in the end.

About the "in" and "in_es6" functions in snippets.py, the difference with the dict is that i consider it a core Python semantic, instead what could be a best fit for the "dict" python class in js land is left to the judgement of the developer. Don't need ES6 stuff and your keys are strings? Use the normal JS object class. You want to have instances or integers as keys and you want to use the JS iterator protocol at the possible cost of a possible slow down due to polifills? Use an ES6 instance of Map or WeakMap.

About the variable scoping, i'm interested in any real bug of course :-) . I do not know what are you referring to but beware that var statements in JS are hoisted, so a variable declared in the middle of a function body is available in all the body.

